+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Xqem93UCdtBP56VBP7gnzp","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 60 tests pass currently. Now I have all the information needed for a thorough review. Here is my complete analysis.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Plugin Implementations vs Test Files\n\nAll 60 tests across 8 plugins currently pass. However, I have identified several issues where the implementation contains bugs that tests either do not cover, or where tests would fail under specific edge conditions. Below are the findings organized by priority.\n\n---\n\n### HIGH PRIORITY ISSUES\n\n---\n\n#### H1. `markdown-ext.ts` -- Admonition regex fails when content does not end with a newline before closing `:::`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, line 4\n\n```typescript\nreturn content.replace(/^:::(note|warning|tip)\\n([\\s\\S]*?)^:::/gm, (_match, type: string, body: string) => {\n```\n\nThe regex uses `^:::` with the multiline flag, meaning `:::` must appear at the start of a line. This requires the closing `:::` to be preceded by a newline. However, look at the test inputs:\n\n**File:** `/workspace/tests/plugins/markdown-ext.test.ts`, lines 59, 66, 73\n\n```typescript\n{ content: ':::note\\nThis is a note.\\n:::' }\n{ content: ':::warning\\nBe careful!\\n:::' }\n{ content: ':::tip\\nHelpful hint.\\n:::' }\n```\n\nThese tests pass because the body text ends with `\\n` before `:::`. But the regex pattern `([\\s\\S]*?)^:::` with the `m` flag requires `:::` to be at the start of a line -- meaning there must be a `\\n` immediately before it. If a user writes an admonition where the closing `:::` is on the same line as the last content character (no trailing newline in the body), the regex will not match and the admonition will be silently passed through unprocessed.\n\nAdditionally, if there is a multi-line admonition body, the `body.trim()` call trims the captured body. But the regex `([\\s\\S]*?)` is non-greedy and combined with `^:::` (multiline), which means it matches from the opening through to the very first `:::` at the start of any line. If the content within the admonition itself contains a line starting with `:::`, the regex will match too early, truncating the admonition body.\n\n**Impact:** Silent data corruption -- admonitions with `:::` in their body text will be incorrectly truncated.\n\n---\n\n#### H2. `markdown-ext.ts` -- Footnote regex only matches numeric footnote IDs (`\\d+`), but test never verifies non-numeric IDs are rejected\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 13 and 19\n\n```typescript\nconst withoutDefs = content.replace(/^\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]:\\s*(.+)$/gm, ...);\nconst withRefs = withoutDefs.replace(/\\[\\^(\\d+)\\]/g, ...);\n```\n\nThe regex restricts footnote IDs to digits only (`\\d+`). Standard Markdown footnote syntax (`[^label]`) allows alphanumeric identifiers. If a user writes `[^note1]: Some text`, it will not be processed. This is a design limitation that should at minimum be documented, but tests never exercise this boundary to confirm the intentional restriction.\n\n**Impact:** Users following standard markdown conventions with non-numeric footnote IDs will get broken output -- the definition text will remain in-line as visible text, and the reference will be rendered literally as `[^note1]`.\n\n---\n\n#### H3. `rss-feed.ts` -- `escapeXml` does not escape single quotes (apostrophes)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts`, lines 3-5\n\n```typescript\nfunction escapeXml(str: string): string {\n  return str.replace(/&/g, '&amp;').replace(/</g, '&lt;').replace(/>/g, '&gt;').replace(/\"/g, '&quot;');\n}\n```\n\nThe XML specification defines five predefined entities: `&`, `<`, `>`, `\"`, and `'`. The single quote (`'` -> `&apos;`) is missing. If a site title or post title contains an apostrophe (e.g., \"John's Blog\"), the generated XML could produce malformed output in contexts where the value appears inside single-quoted attributes.\n\nThe tests never exercise titles containing special XML characters, so this bug is completely untested.\n\n**Impact:** Potentially malformed RSS XML output for sites whose titles or post titles contain apostrophes.\n\n---\n\n#### H4. `search-index.ts` -- `stripHtml` does not handle HTML entities, producing garbled search text\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/search-index.ts`, lines 3-5\n\n```typescript\nfunction stripHtml(html: string): string {\n  return html.replace(/<[^>]+>/g, '').trim();\n}\n```\n\nIf the HTML content contains entities like `&amp;`, `&lt;`, `&gt;`, `&quot;`, or `&#123;`, these will be left in the stripped text verbatim. A search for \"Tom & Jerry\" would require the user to search for \"Tom &amp; Jerry\" to find a match in the index.\n\nThe tests never exercise content with HTML entities, so this is undetected.\n\n**Impact:** Degraded search experience for any content containing HTML entities, which is extremely common in real-world content (ampersands in text, code samples containing angle brackets, etc.).\n\n---\n\n#### H5. `rss-feed.ts` -- Content inside `<![CDATA[` can break if it contains the literal string `]]>`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts`, line 28\n\n```typescript\n<description><![CDATA[${file.content}]]></description>\n```\n\nIf `file.content` contains the literal string `]]>`, the CDATA section will be prematurely terminated, producing invalid XML. This is a well-known XML pitfall. The standard mitigation is to split CDATA sections at `]]>` boundaries or to escape the content differently.\n\nNo test exercises content containing `]]>`.\n\n**Impact:** Invalid RSS XML output that will break RSS readers for any post whose rendered HTML contains the literal sequence `]]>`.\n\n---\n\n#### H6. `sitemap.ts` -- URLs in sitemap are not XML-escaped\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/sitemap.ts`, lines 14-16\n\n```typescript\nconst urlEntries = urls\n  .map(url => `  <url>\\n    <loc>${url}</loc>\\n  </url>`)\n  .join('\\n');\n```\n\nThe `url` values come from `config.baseUrl` concatenated with output keys. If any output key contains XML-special characters (e.g., `&` in a query string -- or a tag name with `&` generated by the taxonomy plugin), the sitemap XML will be invalid.\n\nThe `rss-feed.ts` plugin has an `escapeXml` function but `sitemap.ts` does not use any escaping at all. The tests never exercise paths containing special characters.\n\n**Impact:** Invalid sitemap XML if any output path or base URL contains `&`, `<`, `>`, or other XML-special characters.\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM PRIORITY ISSUES\n\n---\n\n#### M1. `asset-pipeline.ts` -- Does not handle `url()` references in inline CSS\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/asset-pipeline.ts`, lines 8-17\n\nThe plugin only rewrites `src=\"./...\"` and `href=\"./...\"` patterns. Inline styles with `url(./image.png)` or `background: url('./bg.jpg')` will not be caught. While the current tests do not test for this, it is a significant gap for a production asset pipeline.\n\n**Impact:** Asset references in inline styles will remain as broken relative paths.\n\n---\n\n#### M2. `asset-pipeline.ts` -- The `src`/`href` regex does not handle single-quoted attributes\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/asset-pipeline.ts`, lines 8 and 14\n\n```typescript\ncontent = content.replace(/src=\"\\.\\/([^\"]+)\"/g, ...);\ncontent = content.replace(/href=\"\\.\\/([^\"]+)\"/g, ...);\n```\n\nHTML attributes can use single quotes (`src='./image.png'`) or even no quotes. The regex only matches double-quoted attributes. If upstream HTML generation ever uses single quotes (which is valid HTML), those assets will not be rewritten.\n\n**Impact:** Silent failure to rewrite asset paths in single-quoted HTML attributes.\n\n---\n\n#### M3. `markdown-ext.ts` -- `transformContent` is async but `marked.parse()` is imported dynamically every single invocation\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 49-50\n\n```typescript\nconst { marked } = await import('marked');\ncontent = await marked.parse(content);\n```\n\nEvery call to `transformContent` performs a dynamic `import('marked')`. While Node.js caches module imports, the dynamic import syntax still incurs overhead from the promise machinery on every invocation. For a static site with hundreds of files, this adds unnecessary latency. More critically, if the `marked` module is not installed, the error will only surface at content transform time (not at plugin creation time), making debugging harder.\n\nThe test on line 88 (`handles empty content`) exercises the early-return path where `content` is falsy (empty string). However, looking at line 37:\n\n```typescript\nif (!content) {\n  return { ...file, content: '' };\n}\n```\n\nAn empty string `''` is falsy in JavaScript, so it takes the early return. But what if `content` is `undefined`? The type says `content: string`, but at runtime if someone passes `undefined`, the check `!content` would catch it. This is a minor type-safety observation, not a functional bug.\n\n**Impact:** Performance degradation for large sites; late failure if `marked` is missing.\n\n---\n\n#### M4. `taxonomy.ts` -- `afterBuild` generates HTML with un-escaped user-provided data\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/taxonomy.ts`, lines 24-34\n\n```typescript\nconst items = files.map(f => `<li><a href=\"/${f.slug}.html\">${f.title}</a></li>`).join('\\n');\nconst html = `...\n<h1>Tag: ${tag}</h1>\n...`;\n```\n\nNeither `f.title`, `f.slug`, nor `tag` are HTML-escaped. If a file title contains `<script>alert('xss')</script>`, it will be injected directly into the generated HTML. While this is a static site generator (so the threat model is different from a web app), it is still a code quality concern -- user frontmatter data should be escaped before embedding in HTML.\n\nThe tests never exercise titles containing HTML-special characters.\n\n**Impact:** Potential XSS in generated tag pages if file titles or tags contain HTML characters.\n\n---\n\n#### M5. `dev-server.ts` -- Does not include non-HTML output entries (like `search-index.json`, `feed.xml`) as routes\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/dev-server.ts`, lines 14-18\n\n```typescript\nfor (const path of ctx.output.keys()) {\n  if (path.endsWith('.html')) {\n    routes.push({ path: `/${path}`, handler: 'static' });\n  }\n}\n```\n\nOnly `.html` files are added as content routes. Other output files like `feed.xml`, `search-index.json`, and `sitemap.xml` are not added as routes (though the search index gets its own special field). This means the dev server configuration will not have routes for the RSS feed or sitemap.\n\nThe test on line 71 (`config includes content routes`) only checks `.html` files and never verifies that `feed.xml` or `sitemap.xml` have routes.\n\n**Impact:** RSS feed and sitemap will not be servable in dev mode unless handled by a fallback mechanism.\n\n---\n\n#### M6. `rss-feed.ts` -- `pubDate` format is raw ISO date string, not RFC 822 required by RSS 2.0\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/rss-feed.ts`, line 23\n\n```typescript\nconst pubDate = file.date ? `      <pubDate>${file.date}</pubDate>\\n` : '';\n```\n\nRSS 2.0 requires `<pubDate>` to be in RFC 822 format (e.g., `Mon, 01 Jan 2024 00:00:00 GMT`). The implementation passes through the raw date string from the content file (e.g., `2024-01-01`), which is not valid RFC 822. Many RSS readers will fail to parse this date or ignore it.\n\nThe test on line 37 uses `date: '2024-01-01'` and only checks for the presence of `<pubDate>` -- it never validates the format.\n\n**Impact:** Non-compliant RSS feed dates. Many RSS readers will not correctly parse or display publication dates.\n\n---\n\n#### M7. `markdown-ext.ts` -- Footnotes are always rendered in `Map` insertion order, which coincidentally matches definition order, but the `<ol>` implies numeric ordering\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/markdown-ext.ts`, lines 26-32\n\n```typescript\nconst items = Array.from(footnotes.entries())\n  .map(([id, text]) => `<li id=\"fn-${id}\">${text}</li>`)\n  .join('\\n');\nreturn `\\n<section class=\"footnotes\">\\n<ol>\\n${items}\\n</ol>\\n</section>`;\n```\n\nThe footnotes are rendered inside an `<ol>` (ordered list), but the list items get their numbering from HTML's auto-numbering, not from the `id` attribute. If footnote definitions appear in a different order than their numeric IDs (e.g., `[^2]` defined before `[^1]`), the rendered `<ol>` numbering will not match the footnote reference numbers. The `<li>` will be numbered \"1\" by the browser but have `id=\"fn-2\"`.\n\nThe tests never exercise out-of-order footnote definitions.\n\n**Impact:** Confusing footnote numbering when definitions appear out of order in the source document.\n\n---\n\n#### M8. `search-index.ts` -- `stripHtml` regex can fail on malformed HTML with `>` inside attribute values\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/plugins/search-index.ts`, lines 3-5\n\n```typescript\nfunction stripHtml(html: string): string {\n  return html.replace(/<[^>]+>/g, '').trim();\n}\n```\n\nThe regex `<[^>]+>` will incorrectly split a tag like `<img alt=\"a > b\">` at the first `>` inside the attribute value, leaving the text ` b\">` visible in the search index. While uncommon, this is a known limitation of regex-based HTML stripping.\n\n**Impact:** Garbled search index entries for content containing `>` in HTML attribute values.\n\n---\n\n### SUMMARY TABLE\n\n| ID | Severity | Plugin | Issue |\n|----|----------|--------|-------|\n| H1 | HIGH | markdown-ext | Admonition regex silently fails if body contains a line starting with `:::` |\n| H2 | HIGH | markdown-ext | Footnotes restricted to numeric IDs only; non-numeric IDs silently broken |\n| H3 | HIGH | rss-feed | `escapeXml` missing single-quote escaping (`&apos;`) |\n| H4 | HIGH | search-index | `stripHtml` does not decode HTML entities in search text |\n| H5 | HIGH | rss-feed | CDATA section breaks if content contains literal `]]>` |\n| H6 | HIGH | sitemap | URLs not XML-escaped; `&` in paths produces invalid XML |\n| M1 | MEDIUM | asset-pipeline | CSS `url()` references not rewritten |\n| M2 | MEDIUM | asset-pipeline | Single-quoted `src`/`href` attributes not matched |\n| M3 | MEDIUM | markdown-ext | Dynamic `import('marked')` on every invocation (performance) |\n| M4 | MEDIUM | taxonomy | Un-escaped HTML in generated tag pages (XSS potential) |\n| M5 | MEDIUM | dev-server | Non-HTML outputs (feed.xml, sitemap.xml) missing from routes |\n| M6 | MEDIUM | rss-feed | `pubDate` uses raw ISO string instead of RFC 822 format |\n| M7 | MEDIUM | markdown-ext | Footnote `<ol>` numbering mismatches IDs when definitions are out of order |\n| M8 | MEDIUM | search-index | Regex-based `stripHtml` fails on `>` inside attribute values |\n\n---\n\n### WHAT WAS DONE WELL\n\n- All 8 plugins follow a consistent factory pattern (`createXxxPlugin()`) returning the `Plugin` interface.\n- Dependencies between plugins are correctly declared (e.g., `search-index` depends on `markdown-ext` and `syntax-highlight`).\n- The `BuildContext.data` map is used consistently for inter-plugin communication (asset manifests, taxonomy tags, dev-server config).\n- Tests are well-structured with proper helpers (`makeCtx`, `makeFile`) and cover the primary happy paths.\n- The `taxonomy` plugin correctly normalizes tag casing and the test explicitly verifies it.\n- The `asset-pipeline` plugin correctly accumulates assets across multiple `transformContent` calls into a single manifest.\n- The `rss-feed` plugin correctly sorts by date with undated posts pushed to the end."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ad752e9 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 35338\ntool_uses: 23\nduration_ms: 111957</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"564c26e2-ad17-491e-9d10-f6e4f67df875","uuid":"410a3f82-37ad-4a9c-87d4-bb95ae5102ec","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":